Bring up the wireless interface
This is the host workstation's own wireless interface, switched into monitor mode so it can see the over-the-air attack traffic.
	1	Open a native Linux terminal window on the workstation.
	2	Bring the wireless interface down so you can change its state:


   sudo ip link set wlan0 down

	3	Switch the card into monitor mode, bring it back up, and lock it to the training router's channel. Channel 6 is only an example, so use your room's channel:


   sudo iw wlan0 set monitor control
   sudo ip link set wlan0 up
   sudo iw dev wlan0 set channel 6

If wlan0 is not your wireless interface, list your devices first and use the correct name everywhere wlan0 appears:


iw dev

C. Load the debug toolchain

This is the OpenOCD bridge that talks to the target over SWD through the Debug Probe. It is the same toolchain Lab 4.1 uses to flash the hardened firmware.

	1	Confirm OpenOCD reaches the target. Run it against the CMSIS-DAP interface and the RP2040 target:


   sudo openocd -f interface/cmsis-dap.cfg -f target/rp2040.cfg -c "adapter speed 1000"

A clean start shows the VID, the PID, and a valid DPIDR hash (for example, 0x0bc12477). That confirms the SWDIO and SWCLK lines are live.

	2	When you flash in Lab 4.1, the toolchain runs at the faster adapter speed with the program command added on the end:


   sudo openocd -f interface/cmsis-dap.cfg -f target/rp2040.cfg -c "adapter speed 5000" -c "program secure_app.elf verify reset exit"
